<subSubSection id="1CDF5F80FFBEFFE46DC2FEF8FCDEAA9B" pageId="26" pageNumber="1539" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="547A0C0BFFBEFFE46DC2FEF8FCDEAA9B" blockId="26.[178,1084,357,409]" pageId="26" pageNumber="1539">
Etymology: The trivial name 
<emphasis id="66B1D019FFBEFFE46F46FEF8FD19AA78" box="[566,652,357,378]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="1539">subgilva</emphasis>
is a Latin adjective derived from prefix - 
<emphasis id="66B1D019FFBEFFE46DC2FE1EFF40AA9A" box="[178,213,387,408]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="1539">sub</emphasis>
(= less than) and 
<emphasis id="66B1D019FFBEFFE46CFAFE1EFE53AA9A" box="[394,454,387,408]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="1539">gilvus</emphasis>
(= yellow). I refer to the elytral color.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
